author: @sirslap4255
text: if anyone is still watching in 2024, instead of using pandas's data reader you can just use yahoo finance's own library  #Remember to pip install yfinance import datetime as dt import matplotlib.pyplot as plt from matplotlib.pyplot import style import pandas as pd import yfinance as yf  #Style of graph in future usage style.use('ggplot')  #Start and end dates of the data start = dt.datetime(2020,1,2) end = dt.datetime(2024,1,2)  #prints data from yahoo finance from the tail (from 2023) df = yf.download('GOOG', start=start, end=end) print(df.tail())

author: @eugenefdscodes
text: Man I had so many errors come up when I tried to run this! But I fixed them all (as of 2/14/2023). Here‚Äôs how:  The first error was this annoying type error: ‚Äústring indices must be integers‚Äù for the df=web.DataReader(.... line.   It looks like this is an issue with pandas_datareader.data itself. Apparently Yahoo prevents it from scraping stock info correctly as of Dec 2022 so it does not work.   But I fixed it by importing a different module called yfinance. You have to install it by opening up a terminal in your IDE (I use pycharm) and then typing in ‚Äúpip install yfinance‚Äù  Once that‚Äôs installed, you then add ‚Äúimport yfinance as yf‚Äù to the top of your code along with all of the other import statements.   The next step is to add one line right below all the import statements: yf.pdr_override(). This means that whenever you‚Äôre using a function from pandas_datareader, yfinance will swoop in and solve it instead.   Then, you need to change the acronym (not sure what it‚Äôs called) for pandas_datareader.data from ‚Äúweb‚Äù as sentdex wrote to ‚Äúpdr‚Äù everywhere in your code.   Lastly, remove the ‚Äúyahoo,‚Äù argument in the web.DataReader(‚ÄôTSLA‚Äô, ‚Äòyahoo‚Äô, start, end) line. If you don‚Äôt, then it‚Äôll give you this error: ‚ÄúValueError("time data 'yahoo' does not match format ‚Äò%Y-%m-%d‚Äô‚Äù)‚Äù  If you remove yahoo, it should just have ‚Äú(‚ÄòTSLA‚Äô, ‚Äòstart‚Äô, ‚Äòend‚Äô)‚Äù. And then finally, it should work. Hope this helps!

author: @topraman33
text: Google, Yahoo and recently Morningstar (https://stackoverflow.com/questions/51630874/getting-a-request-error-404-in-python-while-accessing-an-api) don't appear to work at the moment. The only one I was able to get working was quandl:  ```df = web.DataReader("TSLA", 'quandl', start, end)'''  You'll have to reverse the data frame so that it's in the same order as sentdex's:  ```df = df.reindex(index=df.index[::-1])'''  Beware that the column labels will be different (e.g. "AdjClose" instead of "Adj Close").  Also for anyone struggling with importing pandas_datareader, this may be your fix:  https://stackoverflow.com/questions/50394873/import-pandas-datareader-gives-importerror-cannot-import-name-is-list-like
